{
  "doc_id": "15418",
  "text": "In addition to the well-characterized circuitry of the basal forebrain, local adenosine has been implicated as an important regulator of the homeostatic drive to sleep [CITATION_1] . Adenosine, a by-product of ATP degradation, increased in the basal forebrain following sleep deprivation [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] and basal forebrain administration of adenosine increased NREM, REM, as well as delta power during NREM sleep [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . Similarly, administration of an agent that caused increased wake and decreased NREM and REM sleep was associated with decreased adenosine in the substantia innominata [CITATION_6] . Therefore, modulation of adenosine in the basal forebrain is a potential mechanism for anestheticinduced hypnosis.",
